    <title>Combined summary - Refreshed BIP324</title>
    <updated>2023-06-16T01:35:53.106051+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-November/021201.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers have been discussing the allocation of message IDs in the network with the addition of BIP324. They considered different ways to increase space while being conservative, including treating the first bit as a 2-byte message ID or using an explicit signaling system. Pieter Wuille suggested merging short and long command structures into a single variable-length command structure with 1-12 byte encodings where the top bit of each byte indicates whether another byte follows. Another suggestion was to use "SHORTMSG" to specify an array of tables supported and, once both sides support the table, send "SENDSHORTMSG" to choose the table used to abbreviate messages sent, as well as any modifications to that table. In October 2022, Bitcoin developers discussed the mapping table between 1-byte IDs and commands. It was proposed to start with a fixed initial table managed by the BIP process directly and switch to dynamically negotiating the mapping if collisions become a concern. The use of a novel 1-byte message was also discussed, and it was recommended against reserving a byte for one-shot messages and avoiding it for existing one-shot messages.On February 17th, 2023, Anthony Towns suggested that short id 0 be reserved for long commands and short ids 1-255 are available for use as aliases of particular long commands. This would avoid variable-length encoding questions and reduce how much information a passive observer could learn about application level features. Additionally, it would drop VERSION, VERACK, GETADDR, SENDADDRV2, SENDHEADERS, and SENDTXRCNCL from bip 324 currently being used. Further discussions were held on the negotiation process of short IDs. It was suggested that two negotiation steps would be necessary for negotiating the mapping table and choosing a mutually recognized table. However, Pieter Wuille argued that if all negotiation of the mapping table took place just once before VERACK and without using short commands, there would be no need for re-negotiating short commands after they are already in use. This could simplify some implementations.In a recent discussion on the Bitcoin-dev mailing list, the topic of having a uniform encoding scheme for Bitcoin's p2p protocol was raised. The original proposal suggested that new commands could be introduced as short ones only, but concerns were raised about the scarcity of 1-byte message type IDs and the lack of a coordination mechanism for multiple in-flight BIPs proposing new message types. Solutions proposed included uniform encoding using the high-bit and making type IDs negotiable per direction per connection. Pieter Wuille suggested merging short and long command structures into a single variable-length command structure with 1-12 byte encodings where the top bit of each byte indicates whether another byte follows. This creates a uniform space for assigning commands, eliminating the need to treat short-binary and long-alphabetic commands as distinct.Overall, the discussions on Bitcoin-dev mailing list suggest that a uniform encoding scheme can be used for message identifiers in the p2p protocol. This would simplify the implementation process and help save bandwidth. However, there are different opinions on how to implement it and whether it optimizes for the right goals. Meanwhile, the BIP324 proposal is being reviewed for its features and changes made since the last public appearance.Pieter Wuille, a Bitcoin developer, proposed an idea to improve the protocol by introducing a uniform encoding scheme without explicit distinction between short and long commands. Wuille clarified that his suggestion is meant as an encoding scheme rather than a replacement for negotiation/coordination mechanism. He also acknowledged that his proposal may be more complex than the alternative and invited others in the community to share their opinions. In response to Wuille's proposal, Vasil Dimov stated that it makes perfect sense to him and quoted Edsger W. Dijkstra about considering the long-term implications of our actions. The proposal for BIP324, a new bitcoin peer-to-peer (P2P) protocol with opportunistic encryption, bandwidth reduction, and upgradability features, has been refreshed with changes since the last public appearance. The community members are invited to review the BIP and Bitcoin Core code.</summary>
